{"source_key":"sha256-0c6145c72f7c68906237355bfab38a2e","record_index":306,"record_hash":"sha256:93adf3d9e01bfe69ce56c6f890c127655bb29658d687bdce0d36b6cacdf2253f","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:09:04.546Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"My pick: **single Rust generator service + one mounted persistent volume**. Keep it dumb.\n\nDo **not** put the live repo cache on S3/R2/Tigris. Git repos and `git-meta-lib` want real filesystem semantics: many small files, locks, atomic renames, random reads, plus `.git/git-meta.sqlite`. Object storage is good for backups or exported projection JSON, not as the working filesystem.\n\nI updated [agent-trail.md](/Users/kiril/src/forge/agent-trail.md:627) with a new **Filesystem / Cache Architecture** section.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n```text\nweb/API facade -> generator HTTP API -> one generator process\n                                  -> one mounted persistent volume\n```\n\nUse:\n\n- **Fly Machine + Fly Volume** as my first choice: lightweight, boring, local persistent disk, daily snapshots. [Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)\n- Render persistent disk or Railway volume are also fine. [Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks), [Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)\n- AWS EFS technically works, including with Lambda/ECS, but I’d skip it for v1. It drags in VPC/IAM/mount targets/network FS concerns. [Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html), [ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\n\nFilesystem layout:\n\n```text\n/var/lib/agent-trail/\n  repos/github/<github-repo-id>/repo.git\n  locks/github/<github-repo-id>.lock\n  db/agent-trail.sqlite\n  snapshots/<snapshot-id>.json\n  tmp/\n```\n\nConcurrency rule: **one writer per repo cache**. Start with one generator process. Later, shard by GitHub repo id if needed. Don’t share the same Git cache across multiple writers.\n\nBackups: don’t overdo it. Repo caches are rebuildable. Use provider volume snapshots. If the local SQLite index becomes important, use a real SQLite backup path like [Litestream](https://litestream.io/getting-started/), not `cp` on a live DB. SQLite’s own WAL docs explicitly warn that WAL doesn’t work over network filesystems, which is another reason to avoid clever shared FS setups. [SQLite WAL](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:09:04.546Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}